@Composable
fun BrokenLazyColumn() {
    // 1. No keys in items
    LazyColumn {
        items(listOf("A", "B", "C")) { item ->
            Text(item)  // No key!
        }
    }

    // 2. Using Column inside LazyColumn
    LazyColumn {
        item {
            Column {  // Bad!
                Text("Item 1")
                Text("Item 2")
            }
        }
    }

    // 3. Forgetting contentPadding
    LazyColumn {
        items((1..100).toList()) { item ->
            Text("Item $item")  // No padding, items touch edges
        }
    }

    // 4. Heavy computation in items
    LazyColumn {
        items((1..100).toList()) { item ->
            Text("Item ${expensiveCalculation()}")  // Runs for each item!
        }
    }

    // 5. Multiple LazyColumns without fixed height
    Column {
        LazyColumn {  // No height constraint!
            items((1..10).toList()) { Text("Item $it") }
        }
        LazyColumn {  // No height constraint!
            items((1..10).toList()) { Text("Item $it") }
        }
    }
}

phase2.explanation:
🤖 **Common LazyColumn mistakes and how to fix them.**

| Mistake | Fix |
|---------|-----|
| No keys | `items(list, key = { it.id })` |
| Nested LazyColumn | Use Column inside item() |
| No contentPadding | `contentPadding = PaddingValues(16.dp)` |
| Heavy computation | `remember { expensive() }` |
| No height constraint | `Modifier.fillMaxSize()` |

**Fixes:**
```kotlin
// 1. Add keys
LazyColumn {
    items(items, key = { it.id }) { item ->
        Text(item.name)
    }
}

// 2. Use Column inside item
LazyColumn {
    item {
        Column {
            Text("Item 1")
            Text("Item 2")
        }
    }
}

// 3. Add contentPadding
LazyColumn(
    contentPadding = PaddingValues(16.dp),
    verticalArrangement = Arrangement.spacedBy(8.dp)
) {
    // items
}

// 4. Remember expensive computation
val result = remember { expensiveCalculation() }

// 5. Add height constraint
Column(
    modifier = Modifier.fillMaxSize()
) {
    LazyColumn(modifier = Modifier.weight(1f)) { }
    LazyColumn(modifier = Modifier.weight(1f)) { }
}
```

**Kotlin-chan says:**
"LazyColumn is powerful. Use it correctly."

